MAVEN BLACK-BRIAR: THE DEBRIEF
Bridge Scene — Triggers when the party returns to Riften with actionable Forelhost intelligence

━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
SCENE: THE PROMOTION
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━
Function: Maven receives the Forelhost intelligence, pays the bounty, and elevates the Lanterns from hired freelancers to permanent, deniable agents of the Black-Briar family. This promotion makes Orion's Grelod contract catastrophically more complicated.
Location: Not the Bee and Barb. The upstairs office of the Black-Briar Meadery — Maven's actual seat of power. The public tavern table was the job interview. This is the boardroom.
Trigger: The party possesses any combination of: Antoine's journals, sealed culture samples, Tears of Rahgot extract, the Strain 2.0 design folder. A housecarl delivers the summons: "Lady Maven wishes to debrief you. Privately. The Meadery. Come alone or with your full company — she doesn't care which. But come."
THE ROOM (Read Aloud)
"The housecarl leads you through the Meadery's main floor — workers scrubbing vats, the smell of honey and lye — and up a narrow staircase to a door you didn't know existed. He knocks twice, opens it, and steps aside.
The room is small and functional. A heavy oak table dominates the space, covered in ledgers, trade route maps, and correspondence bearing seals from half the holds in Skyrim. A single window overlooks the canal. The walls are bare except for a framed copy of the Black-Briar charter and an iron lockbox bolted to the floor.
Maven sits at the head of the table. No housecarls inside — they're outside the door. No drink in her hand. No performance. The amused matriarch from the Bee and Barb is gone. This is the woman who runs Riften's criminal infrastructure, and she is working."
Then improvise from: The scratch of her quill stopping when they enter. The ledgers — columns of numbers, names, shipment dates. The lockbox. The fact that she let them see this room at all.
WHAT'S IN THIS ROOM
The ledgers and trade maps: What they see: Maven's actual books. Shipment routes. Names. If they investigate: Don't. She's watching. Looking too closely at her business while standing in her office is a threat she will remember. If someone does look (Guile TN 16 to read upside-down without being noticed), they see the Meadery's distribution network stretches across four holds. Why planted here: Establishes that they're inside Maven's real operation now. Trust is being extended. It can be revoked.
The iron lockbox: What they see: A heavy strongbox bolted to the floor. If they investigate: That's where the payment is. Also where she keeps things she doesn't trust to banks. Do not touch. Why planted here: The gold is right there. Practical. Maven doesn't make people wait for money.
THE PEOPLE
MAVEN BLACK-BRIAR (The CEO) Voice: Lower than in public. No charm. No amusement. Clipped sentences. She is not performing. When Maven stops performing, it means she considers you useful enough to see the real thing. Body language: Still. Hands folded on the table. Watches their faces while they talk. Misses nothing. Attitude: Impressed but not warm. They delivered. That earns respect, not affection. Cooperates for: Results, intelligence, competence. Pisses her off: Wasting her time. Overvaluing themselves. Lying to her face.
Opening line: "Sit. Show me what you found."
She listens to the full report without interrupting. She examines each piece of evidence as it's presented — the journals, the samples, the extract. Her expression doesn't change, but her hands go still when she reads Antoine's methodology notes. When they mention the name Rahgot, something behind her eyes recalibrates.
THE MOVES
ANY PC → PRESENTING THE INTELLIGENCE
What they want: The 5,000 gold bounty. What they present: Any combination of Forelhost evidence.
The party talks. Maven listens. She does not interrupt. She takes each piece of evidence as it's offered and examines it with the focused attention of someone reading a contract for loopholes. Adapt the following based on what they present and in what order:
When she reads Antoine's journals:
"[She turns pages slowly. Her jaw tightens at the Riften deployment data — the infection rates, the lethality percentages. She reads the passage about Hemming's case twice. When she looks up, her voice is flat.]"
"He documented it. Infection vector: contaminated mead vats. Lethality with treatment: ninety-four percent." She closes the journal. "He tested his weapon on my city. On my son. And he took notes."
When she examines the culture samples:
"[She holds a sealed vial up to the window light. The liquid inside is pale and still.]"
"This is what was in my vats?"
[If confirmed:]
"And you brought it into my office." A beat. The ghost of a smile — not warm. "You have nerve. Good. I hire for nerve."
When she sees the Tears of Rahgot extract:
"What is this?"
[If they explain:]
"An extinct flower. Grows only in the soil of an ancient mass grave." She sets the vial down precisely. "Charming. And this is the binding agent? The thing that makes his poison work?"
[If confirmed:]
"Then we know where his supply comes from. That's leverage."
When she reads the Strain 2.0 folder:
"[This is what changes her posture. She reads the design goals — waterborne, airborne, Restoration-transmissible. She reads the timeline. She sets the folder down on the table, carefully, the way you set down something that might detonate.]"
"Waterborne. Airborne. And it weaponizes the healers." A long exhale through her nose. "Version one killed a dozen people before your priestess stopped it. Version two would empty a city."
When they mention Rahgot — a Dragon Priest, awake, walking:
"[A long silence. Maven is not a woman who is often surprised. She is surprised now. Her fingers, which had been turning a quill, go still. She stares at a point on the table for three full seconds. Then she looks up, and the surprise is gone, replaced by something harder.]"
"Say that again."
[They repeat it.]
"A Dragon Priest. Not a ruin. Not bones in a crypt. A living Dragon Priest, with an army and an alchemist, operating out of a fortress an hour's ride south of my city."
[She stands. Walks to the window. Looks out at the canal. When she speaks again, her back is to them.]"
"Do you know what I thought when the plague hit? I thought it was the Thieves Guild gone rogue. Or a competitor. Or the damn Empire trying to destabilize the Rift before the war heats up. Something human. Something I could buy, blackmail, or break."
[She turns back to face them.]
"This is none of those things. This is an ancient intelligence that views my family, my city, and my entire operation as a petri dish."

MAVEN'S OFFER
Read aloud:
"[She returns to the table. Opens the lockbox. Counts out 5,000 gold in heavy coin purses — five of them, a thousand each. Places them in a neat row on the table. Closes the lockbox. Sits.]"
"That settles the bounty. Five thousand, as agreed. You delivered a name, a location, and proof. The debt is paid."
[She does not push the gold toward them. She leaves it in the center of the table, equidistant from all of them. Then she folds her hands.]
"Now. I am going to make you an offer. I suggest you hear it in full before you start dividing that pile."
[A beat. She looks at each of them in turn — Davinia, Alfonso, Saijah, Orion. She is assessing. Not their strength. Their reliability.]
"A Dragon Priest and his pet alchemist turned my Meadery into a weapon, nearly killed my son, and are building something worse. That is not a bounty. That is a war. And I do not fight wars with mercenaries I hire by the job."
"So here is what I propose."
[She leans forward. Her voice drops — not for secrecy, but for weight.]
"You hunt Antoine and his master. You dismantle their entire operation — every vial, every journal, every culture dish. You bring me their research. And when you find Antoine..."
[She pauses. Her eyes are cold and patient.]
"...you bring him to me. Alive. I have questions for him that require a personal conversation."
"In return, the Black-Briar family becomes your patron. Not your employer — your patron. That means funding when you need it. Safe harbor in any hold where my name opens doors — and there are more of those than you think. Access to my network: merchants, couriers, fences, contacts in every city from Solitude to Windhelm. And protection. When someone threatens the Obsidian Lanterns, they threaten the Black-Briar family. My enemies become yours. But yours become mine."
[She straightens.]
"The Obsidian Lanterns become my hand. Unofficial. Deniable. And exceptionally well compensated."
[She lets the silence hold for a full three seconds.]
"Do we have an understanding?"

PLAYER RESPONSES
If they accept:
"[Maven nods once. Just once. The deal is done. She opens the lockbox again and adds two more purses to the pile — the advance.]"
"Good. Two thousand gold advance against future operations. My steward will set up a line of credit with Keerava at the Bee and Barb — food and lodging are on the house when you're in Riften. Consider it an operational expense."
[She picks up the Strain 2.0 folder and places it in her lockbox.]
"I'm keeping this. You keep the journals — you'll need them for the hunt. And one more thing."
[Her voice softens — fractionally. This is as close to sentiment as Maven gets.]
"Hemming wants to meet the people who sent the woman who saved his life. He's sentimental. Indulge him. He's my son and he nearly died. You can give him ten minutes."
If they negotiate terms:
"Name your conditions."
[She listens. For each condition:]
Operational independence: "Reasonable. I don't micromanage. You choose how you complete the objective. I care about results, not methods."
Right to refuse specific contracts: "Also reasonable. I won't send you to do something that makes you useless to me. But understand — if you refuse a job, I'll find someone else. And the next time I have work, I'll remember who said no."
Transparency about her operations: [Her expression hardens.] "No. You work for me. I do not work for you. My business is my business. Your business is whatever I tell you it is. That is non-negotiable."
If they refuse:
"[Her expression doesn't change. Not anger. Not surprise. Something closer to clinical recalculation.]"
"That is... disappointing."
[She pushes the five thousand gold toward them — the bounty, not the advance.]
"The gold is yours. You earned it. Take it."
[She stands. Walks to the window again. Speaks without turning.]
"You should understand that this offer will not be made again. I do not repeat myself. And the next time you need something in the Rift — a favour, a safe house, a door opened, a question answered — you will find that doors which were open are now merely... closed."
[She turns.]
"Not locked. Just closed. There is a difference. But you'll feel it."
[She gestures to the door.] "My housecarl will show you out."

THE GRELOD COMPLICATION
With the new dynamic established, Orion's problem becomes exponentially worse. The Lanterns are now Maven's trusted agents. Orion is simultaneously carrying a Brotherhood contract to kill one of Maven's key assets. Every path forward has a trap door.
THE DIPLOMATIC PATH (New Option)
If Orion wants to pitch Grelod's removal TO Maven — framing it as operational security advice rather than a Brotherhood hit — this is the moment. He can attempt this during the debrief or request a private word after.
The Roll: Guile TN 18 (Very Hard). This is Maven Black-Briar. She built this system. Telling her it's flawed requires extraordinary nerve and perfect delivery.
SUCCESS:
"[Maven goes very still. She stares at Orion for a long time — five seconds, ten. She is not thinking about whether he's right. She's thinking about what it means that he noticed.]"
"You have a sharp eye." [A pause.] "And the nerve to use it while sitting in my office. That's either very brave or very stupid. I haven't decided which."
[She leans back in her chair. Her fingers steeple.]
"Grelod has been... coasting. On reputation. On sentiment. The city loves her, which means no one looks too closely. That was useful. But useful has a shelf life."
[She looks at Orion directly.]
"Constance. The assistant. She's younger. Quieter. More... manageable. Less likely to attract the kind of attention that ends with a Jarl asking questions I don't want to answer."
[A decision, made in the time it takes to exhale.]
"Handle it. Quietly. The children continue their education. The pipeline doesn't stop. If it does — if there is disruption, if there is noise — I will hold you personally responsible."
[She holds his gaze.]
"And Orion. Do not mistake this for a precedent. You advise me once. That is a gift. You do not advise me twice. That is an insult. Understood?"
SUCCESS WITH COMPLICATION (exactly 18):
[Maven agrees — but her eyes narrow.]
"Before I authorize this... a question. How do you know what the orphanage actually is? That is not public information. That is not Lantern information."
[She waits. She is perfectly still.]
"Someone told you. Who?"
Orion must deflect without revealing the Brotherhood. Second Guile check (TN 14).
├─ SUCCESS → "Krusp Fanck mentioned it during his investigation. He didn't know the details, but he knew the Guild had interests in Honorhall." Maven considers this. Nods. "Krusp. That tracks. Fine. Proceed — but quietly." └─ FAILURE → Maven doesn't challenge him openly. But her expression closes. "Interesting." She says nothing else about it. From this point forward, Maven has one of her people watching Orion specifically.
FAILURE:
"[Maven's expression cools. The warmth — what little there was — is gone.]"
"You have been in my employ for five minutes and you're already auditing my personnel."
[She stands. The meeting is over.]
"I hired you to hunt a Dragon Priest, not to reorganize my city. The orphanage is my concern. Grelod is my asset. And her operations are none of your business."
[She straightens the ledgers on her desk — a dismissal gesture.]
"Stay in your lane, Lantern. You are very good at killing things. I suggest you focus on that."
CRITICAL FAILURE (20):
"[Maven doesn't cool. She sharpens. Her eyes lock onto Orion with the focus of someone who just heard a wrong note in a familiar song.]"
"Someone put you up to this."
[It is not a question.]
"Someone wants Grelod dead and they sent you to get my permission first. Who?"
[She doesn't raise her voice. She doesn't need to. The housecarls outside the door shift their weight.]
"Think very carefully about your next words. Because if someone has taken a contract on one of my people, I need to know who, and I need to know why, and I need to know right now."
Orion must recover. Guile TN 16.
├─ SUCCESS → He deflects convincingly. Maven is not satisfied but drops it — for now. She will investigate independently. └─ FAILURE → Maven begins her own investigation into who wants Grelod dead. Within days, the trail leads to the Black Sacrament. Within a week, she knows the Brotherhood is involved. The Lanterns' position in Riften becomes very, very fragile.

GM NOTES
Maven's offer is genuine. She is not manipulating them — she is making a rational business decision. The Lanterns are dragon-killers with intelligence-gathering capability. That's worth more than 5,000 gold. She wants to lock them down before someone else does.
The promotion is a cage. It's a golden cage with excellent amenities, but it's still a cage. Once they're "her people," walking away becomes difficult. Refusing a job becomes political. And every secret they carry — Alfonso's plague, Orion's Brotherhood, Davinia's Crown — becomes leverage if Maven ever discovers them.
The Grelod pitch is Orion's moment. If his player thinks of it, it's brilliant — he solves the Brotherhood contract, satisfies Maven, and maintains cover. TN 18 is very hard but reachable for a character built for social manipulation. If the player doesn't think of it, don't suggest it. The other paths (silent kill, theatrical kill, exposure) are all still available and all still have consequences.
Do not rush this scene. Let Maven's silence after the Rahgot revelation land. Let the offer sit. Let the players discuss among themselves whether they want to be Maven's agents. The decision they make here reshapes their relationship with the most powerful civilian in the Rift for the rest of the campaign.

